{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"26f62f58-013c-4dff-9696-210850abf86d","content":"The request is a bit ambiguous. You're already using `IFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions`, which is itself an abstraction. Could you clarify what you mean by \"file system wrapper\"? For example:\n\n1. **A simplified facade** — a custom `IFileSystemService` with only the operations your app needs, wrapping `IFileSystem`\n2. **A decorator** — a wrapper adding cross-cutting concerns (logging, retry, metrics) around `IFileSystem`\n3. **Something else?**\n\nWhat operations do you need exposed, and what extra behavior (if any) should the wrapper add?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"076f7d12-93ac-4334-b6c7-9c8edb3b8ec4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a simple codebase using `System.IO.Abstractions`'s `IFileSystem`. They want me to generate a file system wrapper. \n\nBut wait - they're already using `IFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions`, which IS the abstraction/wrapper. What kind of wrapper do they want?\n\nTypically when someone says \"generate a file system wrapper\" and they're already using `IFileSystem`, they might want:\n1. A custom wrapper/adapter around the real file system that implements `IFileSystem`\n2. A simpler custom interface that wraps `IFileSystem`\n3. A testable wrapper\n\n\n4. A wrapper with additional functionality like logging or error handling\n\nSince `System.IO.Abstractions` already provides `FileSystem` as the concrete implementation, they probably want a custom wrapper class that either delegates to `IFileSystem` with added features, or a simplified interface that wraps the existing abstraction. A wrapper makes sense for exposing only the operations needed, adding logging or other cross-cutting concerns, and simplifying testing. I'll create a straightforward `IFileSystemWrapper` interface with a concrete implementation that wraps `IFileSystem` and provides common file and directory operations that the application